  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Published in 2024 by Peter Lang Verlag, <em>The Irish Against the War</em>, edited by Marie-Violaine Louvet, is a recently released contribution to Irish studies that currently sits in the earliest stages of its scholarly life. With no recorded citations to date and modest library holdings, the book has yet to accumulate a measurable citation footprint, though its placement within a well-established academic series positions it for gradual engagement by specialists in the field.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\"><em>The Irish Against the War</em> enters the scholarly conversation as part of the <em>Reimagining Ireland</em> series published by Peter Lang, a long-running series dedicated to interdisciplinary and critical perspectives on Irish culture, history, and identity. The volume is an edited collection comprising two chapters, with contributor David Clare among the core network of authors brought together under Louvet's editorial direction. The series itself is actively expanding, with peer volumes addressing topics ranging from conflict and peace in Northern Ireland to Irish borderlands writing and satirical fiction, situating Louvet's volume within a vibrant and ongoing scholarly project.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's conceptual orientation, as reflected in subject classification, is anchored most strongly in Irish studies, with secondary dimensions touching on history and, to a lesser extent, philosophy and linguistics. This interdisciplinary framing suggests the volume may speak to readers working across literary, historical, and cultural methodologies \u2014 a breadth that is characteristic of the <em>Reimagining Ireland</em> series at large. The thematic focus on Irish opposition to war offers a distinct angle within Irish historiography and cultural studies, engaging questions of pacifism, dissent, and national identity that remain pertinent in contemporary scholarly and public discourse.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">At this early stage, library holdings are limited to a small number of institutions, and no citation activity has been recorded in open scholarly indexes. This is not unusual for a specialized academic volume published within the past year, and it is worth noting that books of this type \u2014 focused monographs and edited collections in area studies \u2014 typically accrue their readership and scholarly response over a longer horizon than journal articles. The absence of immediate citation data should therefore be read as a reflection of recency rather than of scholarly relevance.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Looking ahead, the book's integration into the <em>Reimagining Ireland</em> series, which continues to produce new volumes through 2025 and 2026, provides an institutional context that may support discovery by course designers, researchers, and librarians working in Irish studies. As awareness of the volume grows within specialist communities, its contribution to the historiography of Irish anti-war sentiment and dissent will be better positioned to register in citation networks and teaching adoption records.</p>",
